result.execSummary:
The defendant Teandre T. Nicholson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Manufacture/Deliver THC (<=200g) [Modifiers: Second and Subsequent Offense, PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(h)1.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Defendant Teandre T. Nicholson in court, in custody, with attorney Andrew R Rider.    District Attorney's Office Law Intern and Abbey Nickolie, Assistant District Attorney appeared for the State of Wisconsin. 
Defendant entered a plea of guilty to count 1. Court conducted plea colloquy with defendant. Court found defendant of count 1.
Count 2 dismissed and read-in.

The Defendant was sentenced to the following:

IMPOSED SENTENCE of: 

3 YEARS IMPRISONMENT (CREDIT -  0 days) CONSECUTIVE TO PRESENT SENTENCE
  -  1 YEAR(S) OF INITIAL CONFINEMENT
  -  2 YEAR(S) OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION;

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION:  
*AODA Assessment and follow through with any treatment recommended;
*No Use or Possession of alcohol, controlled substances or drug paraphernalia.
*No Use or Possession of prescription drugs without a valid prescription;
*Any valid prescription drugs must be taken only in the manner in which they are prescribed.
*Inform Agent of all prescriptions
*Follow through with any treatment and/or counseling recommended by Agent;
*Maintain employment and/or combination of schooling 
*DNA sample to be provided if not yet previously done.

COURT COSTS:  $268.00 to be paid as a condition of probation/extended supervision;

DNA SURCHARGE:  $250.00 to be paid as a condition of probation/extended supervision;

Defendant is eligible for Challenge Incarceration Program for both initial confinement and extended supervision.
Defendant is eligible for Substance Abuse Program for both initial confinement and extended supervision.

Felony warnings, voting rights and firearms warnings given.
